|><| 𝐢𝐟 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
      >> The if statement is used to test a particular condition.
      >> It allows you to execute a block of code only if a specified condition is True.
      >> It is known as if-block.

  𝚂𝚢𝚗𝚝𝚊𝚡 ::--

   if condition:
     # code block to execute if the condition is True

  𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎  ::--

    x = 10
    if x > 0:
       print("True")

------------------><--------------------><--------------------

|><| 𝐢𝐟-𝐞𝐥𝐬𝐞 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
      >> This statement provide an else block combined with the if statement.
      >> To execute one block of code if the condition is True and another if it is False.

  𝚂𝚢𝚗𝚝𝚊𝚡 ::--

    if condition:
      # code block if condition is True
    else:
      # code block if condition is False

  𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎  ::--

 >  x = 10
    if x > 5:
       print("True")
    else:
       print("False")

 >  x = 10
    if x < 5:
       print("True")
    else:
       print("False")

------------------><--------------------><--------------------

|><| 𝐢𝐟-𝐞𝐥𝐢𝐟-𝐞𝐥𝐬𝐞 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
      >> This statement use to check multiple conditions in sequence.
      >> It execute the specific block of statement depending upon the true condition among them.

 𝚂𝚢𝚗𝚝𝚊𝚡 ::--

    if condition1:
       # code block if condition1 is True
    elif condition2:
       # code block if condition2 is True
    else:
       # code block if none of the conditions are True

  𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎  ::--

  > x = 15
    if x < 10:
       print("x is less than 10")
    elif x < 20:
       print("x is between 10 and 20")   #it's output.
    else:
       print("x is 20 or more")

  > x = 15
    if x < 10:
       print("x is less than 10")
    elif x < 2:
       print("x is between 10 and 20")
    else:
       print("x is 20 or more")  #it's output

                 <><><><>><><><><><><><><><>
------------------><---------------------><--------------------
                 <><><><>><><><><><><><><><>

|><| 𝐧𝐞𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐝-𝐢𝐟 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
      >> This statement in Python refers to placing one if statement inside another. 
      >> It allows you to test multiple conditions, where the inner condition is checked only if the outer condition is True.

  𝚂𝚢𝚗𝚝𝚊𝚡 ::--

    if condition1:
      # Outer if block
      if condition2:
        # Inner if block
        # Code to execute if both conditions are True

  𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎  ::--

   >  x = 10
      y = 5
      if x > 0:  # Outer condition
         if y > 0:  # Inner condition
            print("Both x and y are positive")

------------------><---------------------><--------------------

|><| 𝐧𝐞𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐝-𝐢𝐟-𝐞𝐥𝐬𝐞 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
      >> This statement in Python refers to having an if-else block inside another if or else block. 
      >> This structure is used when you need to check multiple conditions.

  𝚂𝚢𝚗𝚝𝚊𝚡 ::--

     if condition1:
        if condition2:
           # Code block if condition1 and condition2 are True
        else:
           # Code block if condition1 is True but condition2 is False
     else:
        # Code block if condition1 is False

  𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎  ::--

    x = 10
    y = 5
    if x < 0:  # Outer condition
       if y > 0:  # Inner condition
          print("x and y are both positive")
       else:
          print("x is positive, but y is not positive")
    else:
       print("x is not positive")

                 <><><><>><><><><><><><><><>
